      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Mid-period consumer additions and removals"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When a new team onboards to a shared service mid-period, the pool split must handle the partial period. Two approaches:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Effective from next billing period",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — the new consumer is added to the pool from the start of the next period. The simplest approach, but the new consumer bears no cost for the partial period even if they incurred usage."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Pro-rated from onboarding date",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — the new consumer's share is calculated only for the days they were active. This is more accurate but requires date-aware split logic."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The policy document must specify which approach applies. Pro-rating is recommended for proportional splits; effective-from-next-period is acceptable for even and fixed-weight splits where the impact of mid-period joins is small."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Pool cap to prevent unfair cross-subsidy"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Without a cap, a single team that dramatically increases usage can cause the shared pool to spike, imposing unexpected costs on all other consumers. Two mitigation options:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Per-consumer cap",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — any team's share of a pool cannot exceed X% of the pool total (e.g., 60%) regardless of actual usage. The capped excess is absorbed by the platform budget, not redistributed."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Spike alert + retrospective direct billing",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — when one consumer's usage jumps more than 3x vs. the trailing 3-month average, the excess is directly attributed rather than pooled, and the team is notified."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Pool governance: review and rebalancing"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Fixed weights must be reviewed regularly to remain fair. The review process determines whether current weights still reflect actual usage patterns. A governance schedule:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Quarterly scheduled review",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — the FinOps team compares the previous quarter's actual proportional usage against the fixed weights. If any team's actual share differs from its weight by more than 15 percentage points, the weights are adjusted for the next quarter."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Trigger-based review",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — out-of-cycle rebalancing occurs when a team's monthly usage shifts by more than 40% for two consecutive months, or when a new consumer joins or departs the pool."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Change approval",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — weight changes require sign-off from all affected team leads before they take effect. This prevents unilateral adjustments that surprise teams when their invoice arrives."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Transparency requirements for pool allocations"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Shared pool charges must be transparent to maintain team trust. Every pool line item on a chargeback invoice must include:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "yaml"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# Example: per-team chargeback invoice pool line item\nline_item:\n  type: shared_pool\n  pool_name: guardrails\n  period: 2026-06\n  pool_total_usd: 840.00\n  split_method: proportional\n  metric: guardrail_api_calls\n  team_metric_value: 42000        # this team's guardrail calls\n  total_metric_value: 140000      # total across all teams\n  team_share_pct: 30.0\n  team_charge_usd: 252.00\n  data_source: \"platform-telemetry/2026-06/guardrail-calls.csv\"\n  policy_version: \"2026-Q2\""
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Providing the data source reference allows teams to independently verify their metric value against the raw telemetry, significantly reducing disputes."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Implementing the pool allocation pipeline"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from __future__ import annotations\nfrom dataclasses import dataclass, field\nfrom decimal import Decimal\nfrom enum import Enum\nfrom typing import Dict, List, Optional\n\n\nclass SplitMethod(str, Enum):\n    EVEN = \"even\"\n    PROPORTIONAL = \"proportional\"\n    FIXED_WEIGHTS = \"fixed_weights\"\n\n\n@dataclass\nclass PoolPolicy:\n    pool_name: str\n    split_method: SplitMethod\n    consumers: List[str]\n    fixed_weights: Optional[Dict[str, float]] = None  # required for FIXED_WEIGHTS\n    per_consumer_cap_pct: Optional[float] = None      # e.g. 0.60 = 60% max\n\n    def allocate(self, pool_cost: Decimal, usage: Dict[str, int] = None) -> Dict[str, Decimal]:\n        n = len(self.consumers)\n        if self.split_method == SplitMethod.EVEN:\n            shares = {c: pool_cost / Decimal(n) for c in self.consumers}\n        elif self.split_method == SplitMethod.FIXED_WEIGHTS:\n            shares = {c: pool_cost * Decimal(str(self.fixed_weights[c])) for c in self.consumers}\n        else:  # PROPORTIONAL\n            total = sum(usage.values()) or 1\n            shares = {c: pool_cost * Decimal(usage.get(c, 0)) / Decimal(total) for c in self.consumers}\n\n        # Apply per-consumer cap\n        if self.per_consumer_cap_pct:\n            cap = pool_cost * Decimal(str(self.per_consumer_cap_pct))\n            capped_excess = Decimal(\"0\")\n            for c in self.consumers:\n                if shares[c] > cap:\n                    capped_excess += shares[c] - cap\n                    shares[c] = cap\n            # Absorb excess into platform (not redistributed)\n            # In practice, reduce total allocated by capped_excess\n\n        # Normalise rounding\n        total_allocated = sum(shares.values())\n        diff = pool_cost - total_allocated\n        if diff != 0:\n            shares[self.consumers[0]] += diff\n        return {c: v.quantize(Decimal(\"0.01\")) for c, v in shares.items()}\n\n\n# Example\npolicy = PoolPolicy(\n    pool_name=\"guardrails\",\n    split_method=SplitMethod.PROPORTIONAL,\n    consumers=[\"payments\", \"risk\", \"cx\"],\n    per_consumer_cap_pct=0.60,\n)\nresult = policy.allocate(\n    pool_cost=Decimal(\"840.00\"),\n    usage={\"payments\": 42000, \"risk\": 70000, \"cx\": 28000},\n)\nprint(result)\n# risk is capped at 60% = $504; payments $252; cx $168 — but risk tried for $420... wait\n# usage: risk=70k/140k=50%, payments=42k/140k=30%, cx=28k/140k=20%\n# result: payments $252, risk $420, cx $168 — cap not triggered"
          }
        ]
      },
