      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Pool escalation and exception handling"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Some pools accumulate unexpected spikes due to incidents or platform migrations. Exception-handling rules prevent these events from generating unfair charges:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Platform incident absorption",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — if the platform team caused a cost spike (e.g., a misconfigured guardrail ran redundant calls), that excess is absorbed by the platform budget and excluded from the pool allocation for the period."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Migration cost exclusion",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — when the platform migrates to a new embedding model, the batch re-embedding cost is one-off platform infrastructure spend, not operational usage. It should be excluded from the proportional pool and absorbed centrally."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Agreed floor prices",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — for small teams with very low usage, the proportional share may be too small to create any cost awareness. Setting a minimum floor (e.g., $5/period per registered consumer) ensures all teams remain aware of their shared infrastructure costs."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Common mistakes"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Pooling costs that could be directly tagged",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — if a guardrail makes a downstream API call per agent call, the cost can be tagged at the calling agent layer. Only put costs in a pool when direct tagging is genuinely impossible."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Quarterly pools, monthly billing",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — if weights are set quarterly but billing is monthly, the pool must be re-split monthly using the quarterly weights. Using annual weights for a monthly billing cycle creates large quarterly adjustments."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "No transparency into pool composition",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — teams receiving a chargeback line item for 'platform overhead' without a detailed breakdown cannot understand or optimise their share. Each pool allocation should be accompanied by the pool cost, the split method used, and the team's share metric."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Key takeaways"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Shared cost pools are appropriate only when direct tagging is structurally impossible. Every cost that can be tagged should be tagged."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "The three split methods (even, proportional, fixed weights) have distinct trade-offs. Match the method to the cost's nature: even for true overheads, proportional for usage-driven services, fixed weights for pre-agreed platform investments."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Every pool needs a written, versioned policy that specifies consumers, the split method, the data source, and the review cadence."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Per-consumer caps prevent a single team's usage spike from unexpectedly inflating costs for all other pool members."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}